Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{2} into half moons. Chop the @potato{1} into wedges the thickness of your thumb (no need to peel). Lay the wedges on a #baking tray{} and drizzle over a little @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and toss to coat. Pop on the top shelf of your oven. Cook until golden brown outside and soft inside, ~{30-35%minutes}. Give the baking tray a good shake halfway through cooking.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on low heat. Add the onion and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Add the @balsamic vinegar{3/4} and place a lid on the pan. Cook gently for ~{20%minutes}, stirring once in a while.

Put the @minced beef{250} in a #mixing bowl{}. Add the @ras-el-hanout{3/4} and a pinch of @salt{}. Form the beef into equal-sized burger patties (two each).

> TIP: The ras-el-hanout is pretty spicy. Add less if you don't like it hot!

> TIP: Don't press the meat together too firmly, as this will make the texture of your burger tough.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, gently lay in the burgers. Cook for ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn and cook the other side for ~{5-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If you want to cook the burgers a little more in the middle, you can place them in your oven for a few mins after frying.

When the wedges are 5 mins from being ready, split open the @brioche buns{2} and lay them on top of the wedges to warm through. When warm, pop in the burger.

Serve your Moroccan beef burgers with a spoonful of red onion relish and a dollop of @Greek style yoghurt{1/2}. Arrange some potato wedges and a handful of @baby spinach{1/2} on the side. Enjoy!